Red Hat OpenShift Administration II (DO280) – Detailed Quick Explanation
This course focuses on running and managing an OpenShift cluster in production.
It teaches how to secure, manage users, control resources, manage networking, and update the cluster.
Think of it like this:
Course	Focus
DO180	Deploy applications on OpenShift
DO280	Manage and secure the OpenShift cluster
________________________________________
1. OpenShift Cluster Administration
An OpenShift cluster administrator manages:
•	Users and permissions
•	Applications running in cluster
•	Security policies
•	Network access
•	Resource usage
•	Cluster updates
Cluster admins make sure:
•	Applications run reliably
•	Teams cannot interfere with each other
•	Cluster stays secure
________________________________________
2. Multi-Tenancy (Multiple Teams Using Same Cluster)
What is Multi-Tenancy?
Multi-tenancy means many teams share the same cluster safely.
Example:
Team	Application
Dev Team	Web App
QA Team	Testing Tools
Data Team	Analytics
Each team gets a separate project/namespace.
In OpenShift
Namespace = Project
Command:
oc new-project dev-project
Check projects:
oc get projects
Switch project:
oc project dev-project
This ensures isolation between teams.
________________________________________
3. Authentication
Authentication answers:
Who are you?
OpenShift supports many authentication methods.
Examples:
•	Local users
•	LDAP
•	GitHub
•	OAuth
•	HTPasswd
Example: Login
oc login -u developer -p password https://api.cluster.com
OpenShift checks identity through OAuth server.
________________________________________
4. Authorization (RBAC)
Authorization answers:
What are you allowed to do?
OpenShift uses RBAC (Role Based Access Control).
RBAC Components:
Component	Meaning
Role	Set of permissions
RoleBinding	Assign role to user
ClusterRole	Cluster-wide role
ClusterRoleBinding	Assign cluster role
Example roles:
•	admin
•	edit
•	view
________________________________________
Give User Access
Give developer edit permission to project.
oc adm policy add-role-to-user edit dhruv -n dev-project
Check roles:
oc get rolebindings
________________________________________
5. Resource Quotas
If many teams use a cluster, one team might consume all resources.
Resource quotas prevent this.
Example limit:
•	CPU
•	Memory
•	Pods
•	Storage
________________________________________
Example ResourceQuota YAML
apiVersion: v1
kind: ResourceQuota
metadata:
  name: project-quota
spec:
  hard:
    pods: "10"
    requests.cpu: "4"
    requests.memory: 8Gi
Apply:
oc apply -f quota.yaml
Check quota:
oc describe quota
________________________________________
6. Network Policies
By default pods can communicate with any pod.
This is not secure.
Network policies restrict communication.
Example:
Allow only frontend to talk to backend.
________________________________________
NetworkPolicy Example
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-frontend
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: backend
  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: frontend
Apply:
oc apply -f networkpolicy.yaml
Now only frontend pods can access backend pods.
